challenges.content:
I'm no fan of jargon, but sometimes you just gotta learn it. The "box model" is one such case because the concepts that fall under the box model are vital to being fluent in CSS.
# What is the box model?

The official CSS documentation gives a nice overview:

>  Everything in CSS has a box around it, and understanding these boxes is key to being able to create layouts with CSS, or to align items with other items.

To put this another way, the box model is how elements are visually arranged on a web page. Now let's get a bit more concrete. There are a number of CSS properties that fall under the banner of the box model that we will be concerned with:

* `width` and `height`: How wide or tall an element is.
* `margin`: Visual space between elements.
* `border`: Space around an element between it's `margin` and `padding`.
* `display`: How an element interacts with other elements on the page. 

# The first line of all your CSS: border\-box

Utilizing the box model with regard to `width`,`height`, `margin`, `border`, and `padding` used to be tricky. The _visual_ size of an elementâ€”how large it looks to your eyes on screenâ€”would be calculated as the sum of `width` or `height` \+ `margin` \+ `border` \+ `padding`. This was unintuitive. When you say `width: 300px` you generally expect the element to be `300px` wide\. 

In fact, that behavior is still the default in browsers, which can make it difficult or time consuming to style your applications. However, **there is a better way**\! Enter `box-sizing: border-box`.

```css
* {
    box-sizing: border-box;
}

```

What is this line doing?
* `*` is selecting **everything** on the page. Every element. It's a special selector.
* `box-sizing: border-box` Tells the browser that we want the `width` and `height` properties to determine the _visual_ width and _visual_ height of elements on the page.


## A concrete example

This is all fairly abstract, so here's some code to help. You can drop this into the Sandbox and compare the visual difference between the two `div` elements\. If you run this code in the sandbox you will notice that the content of the first `div` has the exact same width as the entire second `div`. 

```markup
<style>
  strong {
    display: block;
    text-align: center;
  }
  div {
    background: white;
    margin: 0 auto;
    margin-top: 20px;
  }
  .outer {
    background: lightblue;
    width: 300px;
    padding: 20px;
    border: 5px solid tomato;
  }
  .border-box {
    box-sizing: border-box;
  }
</style>
<div class="outer">
  <div>
    <h3>Standard Box Model</h3>
    <p>
      This div shows how the box model works by default. The border, padding and
      width are all added together to get the visual width of the element.
    </p>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="outer border-box">
  <div>
    <h3>Border Box</h3>
    <p>
      This div uses the super fun and interesting
      <code>box-sizing: border-box;</code> property. You can control it's visual
      <code>width</code> and <code>height</code> directly without calculation.
    </p>
  </div>
</div>
<script>
  // This code just calculates the visual width and display is in each div
  for (let el of document.querySelectorAll('.outer')) {
      const rect = el.getBoundingClientRect();
      const label = document.createElement('strong');
      label.textContent = 'Visual Width: ' + rect.width + 'px';
      el.insertAdjacentElement('afterend', label);
  }
</script>

```
# External Resources

* [The CSS box model docs](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Learn/CSS/Building_blocks/The_box_model)

